\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Operational equivalence maps into ontological equivalence.
 Noncontextuality or classical understanding requires Leibniz's principle
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sep-identity-indiscernible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 When it fails we say: it is contextual or quantum.
 Classically, given two object 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

.
 If for every property 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 iff y has 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is ontological identical to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{∀}F\quad(Fx\leftrightarrow Fy)\to x=y.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Contextuality concept emerges when we would describe an ontological reality
 via operationalism.
 If we will be able to show quantitatively the dependence of the context,
 then we can states to assist a quantum signature.
 Quantitatively means that only quantum mechanics can saturate some inequalities
, in our case Englert's inequality.
 First of all, we need some notion of contextuality.
 Then we will focus on our attention on the anomalous weak values (no go
 theorem).
 There exixts an anomalous weak value than we get contextual-dependence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\emph on
Contextuality means that if you have two equivalent experimental procedures,
 there exist two different probability distribution in the hidden variable
 model (ontological model).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We should applying such idea for the Englert's inequality.
 We need to find two equivalent decompositions for a channel.
 One decomposition should be written associate to the disturbance and another
 decomposition which is non perturbed, connected to the visibility.
 Then, if there is no context-dependence Englert's inequality is never violated
 with this value, but if we get the saturation in the inequality, then those
 two decomposition must be different in the hidden variable model, although
 they represent the same channel.
 Alternatively, if you measure an anomalous weak value, than Englert's inequalit
y is violated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Reproducibility and determinism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(
\emph on
Ontological model 
\emph default
).
 An ontological model is complete description of a system without any reference
 to epistemic knowledge or ignorance.
 From the Greek ὄν, genitive ὄντος: "of that which is", is physical, real.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Philosophical discourse traditionally distinguishes between ontology and
 epistemology and generally enforces this distinction by keeping the two
 subject areas separated.
 However, the relationship between the two areas is of central importance
 to Physics, since it is an experimental science.
 For instance, many measurement-related problems force us to consider both
 our knowledge of the states and observables of a system (epistemic perspective)
 and its states and observables, independent of such knowledge (ontic perspectiv
e).
 Ontological and epistemic perspective are strongly related by the operationalis
m.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
Operationalism and realism.
 A researcher in quantum foundations can be operationalist or realist.
 For the operationalist, operators in Hilbert space represent preparation,
 transformation and measurement procedures, specified as lists of instructions
 of what to do in the lab.
 For the realist, there is some deeper reality underlying the equations
 of quantum mechanics that ultimately accounts for why we see the measurements
 we do
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hardy2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the term 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

complete
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\emph default
, in this scenario is reffered to celebrate Eistein-Podolski-Rosen's article
 which states 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

every element of the physical reality must have a counterpar in the physical
 model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\emph default
They say, 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

In a complete model there is an element corresponding to each element of
 reality.
 A sufficient condition for the reality of a physical quantity is the possibilit
y to predicting it with certainty, without disturbing the system (0).
 In quantum mechanics in the case of two physical qunatities described by
 non-commuting operators, the knowledge of one precludes the knowledge of
 the other.
 Then either (1) the description of reality given by the wave function is
 not complete or (2) there two quantities cannot have simultaneous reality.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
Axiom.
 Reproducibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\Mapsto$
\end_inset

 determinism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
In an ontological model for an operational theory, the preparation procedure
 prepares the ontic state of the system.
 If is not the case, we require the introduction of hidden variables.
 Therefore, often we call hidden variable model to refer an ontological
 theory.
 However, there are systems such that the same preparation procedure does
 not imply the same outcome.
 It means that for each outcome does not exist any procedure which garantee,
 if we repeat, to obtain exactly that outcome (determinism 
\begin_inset Formula $\nRightarrow$
\end_inset

reproducibility).
 Nonetheless, we strongly require the opposite implication, hence the same
 preparation procedure implies a deterministic probability distribution
 of ontic states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
Breifly, given the ontological set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, the outcomes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 of measurements are not uniquely determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, but only the probabilities of different outcomes are determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the classical models, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is the phase space and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\left(q,p\right)$
\end_inset

 is the set of generalized coordinates, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 are the all possible values to assign for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q,p\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Noncontextual hidden variable model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align center

\emph on
Either you accept that a particle doesn't have a definite preset value for
 its spin before you measure it (that's the ordinary interpretation of quantum
 mechanics) or you accept that the preset value depends on what other measuremen
ts you decide to make at the same time.
 Both options are strange — take your pick!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Bell-Kochen-Specker) Given 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset

 Hermitian operators such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[A,B\right]=\left[A,C\right]=0$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[B,C\right]\neq0$
\end_inset

, in a noncontextual hidden variable model of quantum theory the value predicted
 to occur in a measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 does not depend on wheter 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 was measured simultaneously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Spekkens) A noncontextual ontological model of an operational theory is
 one wherein if two experimental procedures are operationally equivalent,
 then they have equivalent representation in the ontological model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The role of an operational theory is merely to specify the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(k|,P,T,M\right)$
\end_inset

 of different outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 that may result from a measurement procedure 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, given a particular preparation 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and a particular transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Equivalence class of preparations, transformations, measurements and experimenta
l procedure.
 The equivalence relation of the equivalence class is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\equiv\sim_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $P\sim P'\Leftrightarrow p\left(k|,P,T,M\right)=p\left(k|,P',T,M\right)\qquad\forall T,M$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $T\sim T'\Leftrightarrow p\left(k|,P,T,M\right)=p\left(k|,P,T',M\right)\qquad\forall P,M$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $M\sim M'\Leftrightarrow p\left(k|,P,T,M\right)=p\left(k|,P,T,M'\right)\qquad\forall P,T$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P,T,M\right)\sim\left(P',T',M'\right)\Leftrightarrow p\left(k|,P,T,M\right)=p\left(k|,P',T',M'\right)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
(
\emph on
photon polarization) 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

 denoted msmt procedures which use respectively a piece of polaroid and
 a birifrangent crystal both oriented along the 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 axis.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{4}$
\end_inset

 are respectively identical to 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

, but both oriented along 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}_{\theta'}$
\end_inset

 axis.
 It turns out that after many msmts 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(k|M_{1}\right)=p\left(k|M_{2}\right)=p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(k|M_{3}\right)=p\left(k|M_{4}\right)=p'$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq p'$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}\sim M_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{3}\sim M_{4}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}\not\not\sim M_{j}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j=3,4$
\end_inset

.
 We have two kind features in this experiment: one related to the axis (
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}_{\theta'}$
\end_inset

) and the other related to the object (polaroid, crystal).
 The axis specifies the equivalence class.
 The object, cannot specifies the equivalence class, because we cannot distingui
sh which object we used, therefore a variation of this feature does not
 change the equivalence class of the procedure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(
\emph on
context of experimental procedure)
\emph default
.
 Given an experimental procedure with some features, it can be defined in
 different equivalence classes, by different probability distribution.
 We have two types of features.
 A variantion of the first type of feature gives different probability distribut
ions, hence different equivalence classes.
 This first type of feature is specified by specified the equivalence classe
 that the procedure falls in.
 A variation of the second type of feature cannot specify an equivalence
 class because a variation of it does not change the probability distribution.
 The set of the feature of the second type-those that are not specified
 by specifying the equivalence class- we call 
\emph on
context 
\emph default
of the experimental procedure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the knowledge of the context (we used polaroid or crystal) does
 not enable to predict the outcomes of an experiment any better than if
 only knew the equivalence class (the axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

') of the experimental procedure.
 In the operational framework follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\emph on
noncontextual ontological model of an operational theory 
\emph default
is an attempt to offer an explanation of the success by assuming that there
 exist physical systems that are the subject of the experiment.
 These systems are presumed to have attributes which describe the real state
 of affairs of the system.
 Thus, a specification of which instance of each attribute applies at a
 give time we call the 
\emph on
ontic state 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of the system
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Essentially, you reckon with the ontic, you understand the ontological:
 the ontic is something adequately grasped by something like counting, while
 the ontological is something grasped only adequately when it is seen and
 participated in as significant.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we mathematically expose the ontological model for an operational theory.
 We shall denoted the complete set of the variables in an ontological model
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

, and the space of values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 Given an ontological model we say that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for an operational preparation P, the probability measurement 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 on the ontic states is determined.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}:\Omega\mapsto\left[0,1\right],\:\int_{\Lambda}\mu_{P}\left(\lambda\right)d\lambda=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for an operational msmt M, the probability of obtaining the outcomes labelled
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are determined by a set of indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{M,k}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 over the ontic states, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{M,k}:\Omega\mapsto\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}\xi_{M,k}\left(\lambda\right)=1,\quad\forall\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for an operational transformation T, the transition from the ontic state
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 to the ontic state 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda'$
\end_inset

 is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{T}:\Omega\times\Omega\mapsto\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\Lambda}\Gamma\left(\lambda',\lambda\right)d\lambda'=1,\negthickspace\forall\lambda.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the predictions of the operational theory are reproduced exactly by the
 model
\begin_inset Newline linebreak
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\left[P\right],\left[M\right],\left[T\right]$
\end_inset

 but also 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall P,M,T$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p\left(k|P,T,M\right)=\int_{\Lambda^{2}}\mu_{P}\left(\lambda\right)\Gamma_{T}\left(\lambda',\lambda\right)\xi_{M,k}\left(\lambda'\right)d\lambda d\lambda'.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We would like to specify that in general an experimental procedure in an
 ontological model might depend on both its equivalence class (first kind
 of feature, e.g.
 axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

) and its context (second kind of feature, e.g.
 polaroid or crystal).
 It is natural, however to take into account only the equivalence classes
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\forall\left[P\right],\left[M\right],\left[T\right]\right)$
\end_inset

, as we have seen in the example.
 For each representant of the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $P\sim P'$
\end_inset

 and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $T\sim T'$
\end_inset

 and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $M\sim M'$
\end_inset

 should be 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(k|P,T,M\right)=p\left(k|P',T',M'\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If it is the case the operational model is 
\emph on
noncontextual ontological model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember, we say that two procedure are equivalent 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P,T,M\right)\sim\left(P,T,M\right)'$
\end_inset

 because they prepare the ontic state of the system in precisely the same
 way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Characterization of noncontextuality for preparations) Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 the space of the preparations.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively the equivalence relation of the first and second kind of feature.
 The noncontextual preparation ontological model iff the quotient space
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}/\sim_{1}\equiv\left(\mathcal{P}/\sim_{1}\right)/\sim_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\color red
Can we extend such characterization for msmt and transformation? Yes, immed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Noncontextuality in quantum theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In quantum operational formalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remarkable, for testing a noncontextual theory wheter ontological deterministic
 (e.g.
 Bohm's theory) or indeterministic (e.g.
 Bohr's rule) the appropriate quantities to examine are the epistemic probabilit
ies of different outcomes, rather than the outcomes themselves for a given
 ontic state of the system.
 This is useful to remark the different role of the contextuality and the
 indeterminism.
 Given an ontological deterministic model, with the ontic state 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\left\{ l:\text{ontological variable}\right\} $
\end_inset

 the msmts 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \chi_{I_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

on 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 give a value in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\left\{ \omega:\,\chi_{I_{k}}\left(l\right)=\omega\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Operationally we have access only to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and not to every hidden variables 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 which describe the miscroscopic degree of freedom of the apparatus, therefore
 we always write 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{I_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Given a partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ I_{k}\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall k\;I_{k}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}\cap I_{k'}=\emptyset\:k\neq k'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{k}I_{k}=\Omega$
\end_inset

, the msmts 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \chi_{I_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 are defined by idempotent indicator functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{I_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)=\chi_{I_{k}}^{2}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\Omega}\left(\lambda\right)=\sum_{k}\chi_{I_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{I_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\chi_{I_{k'}}\left(\lambda\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq k'$
\end_inset

.
 Given the complete set of the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 (the ontic state), for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 only a single indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{I_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 in the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \chi_{I_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 receives the value 1 while the others receive the value 0.
 It specifies the probability of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th outcome given the ontic state 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the assumpion of 
\emph on
outcome determinism
\emph default
 of the msmt is determined for all ontic state iff the ontic state 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is represented by the set of idempotent indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \chi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Interestingly, even for objectively deterministic ontological model msmts
 exhibit outcome determinism: the knowledge of the ontic state and the equivalen
ce class is not suffiecient to fix uniquely the outcome.
 It might only fixed uniquely specifying the context of the msmt.
 This means that we are describing not only the system itself, but even
 the environment.
 In order to take into account the environment in the msmt procedure the
 indicator function cannot be idempotent.
 In this description we lose the outcome determinism assumption, but the
 probability distribution either can or cannot depend on the context.
 This latter dependence is required to declare if the model is or not is
 contextual.
 In fact if we required noncontextuality then for all equivalence class,
 all the element are represented by the same set of non-idempotent indicator
 function.

\color red
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Violation of causality principle implies nonlocality, analogously violation
 of independence of the equivalence class implies contextuality.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Because the indicator function for a measurement specifies the dependence
 of the outcome on the ontic state of the system under investigation, and
 not the dependence of the outcome on the ontic state of any systems that
 make up the measurement apparatus or the environment, such a measurement
 must be represented by a non-idempotent set of indicator functions.
 Nonetheless, it may still be the case that for each equivalence class of
 measurements, all the elements of the class are represented by the same
 non-idempotent set of indicator functions, and this is all that is required
 for the measurements to be deemed noncontextual by our definition.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\color inherit
The traditional definition is restore via fine-graning PVM in Hilbert spaces
 of dimensionality three or grater
\color red
(to shed light here)
\color inherit
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following we present three no-go theorem, in particular we proof
 that given an ontological model plus P-noncontextuality (for preparations)
 and T-contextuality (for transformations) is incompatible with quantum
 mechanics (qm).
 Funny, M-contextuality is still compatible with quantum mechanics (Beltrametti-
Bugaski ontological model).
 But if introduce the extra assumption of outcome determinism for unsharp
 msmt then ontological model+M-noncontextuality+outcome determinism is not
 compatible with qm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contextuality for preparation in 2D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:(distinguishability)"

\end_inset

(distinguishability) If two preparation procedures 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 are distinguishable in a single-shot msmt, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{P'}\left(\lambda\right)=0\;\forall\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 (nonoverlapping).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
When it happens, we are able to perfectly distinguish two elements of reality.
 Otherwise we could have ontic states, which are the ontological the same,
 but different operationally speaking.
 It should be cospirational.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:(convex-combination)"

\end_inset

(convex combination) Given two preparation procedures 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

, which respectively correspond on the ontological model the distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P'}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

, we can build 
\begin_inset Formula $P''$
\end_inset

 tossing a coin uniformly random distributed which give 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution on the ontological model for 
\begin_inset Formula $P''$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P''}\left(\lambda\right)=p\mu_{P}\left(\lambda\right)+\left(1-p\right)\mu_{P'}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The convex sum for arbitrary preparation is an easy iteration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Given 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonoverlappingdistribution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:convexsumdistribution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for a noncontextual preparation procedure ontological model for a quantum
 theory 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{x}\Longrightarrow\nexists$
\end_inset

 an ontological distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P_{x}}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\left[P_{x}\right]}\left(\lambda\right)=\mu_{\rho}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 (which satisfied the epistemic outcomes) for an 
\color red
arbitrary
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\noindent
\align block
Let a set of six pure preparations 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{a},P_{b},P_{c},P_{A},P_{B},P_{C}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\psi_{a}=\left(1,0\right) & \mapsto\sigma_{a}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right)\nonumber \\
\psi_{A}=\left(0,1\right) & \mapsto\sigma_{A}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right)\nonumber \\
\psi_{b}=\left(1/2,\sqrt{3}/2\right) & \mapsto\sigma_{b}=\frac{1}{4}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & \sqrt{3}\\
\sqrt{3} & 3
\end{array}\right)\nonumber \\
\psi_{B}=\left(\sqrt{3}/2,-1/2\right) & \mapsto\sigma_{B}=\frac{1}{4}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -\sqrt{3}\\
-\sqrt{3} & 3
\end{array}\right)\nonumber \\
\psi_{c}=\left(1/2,-\sqrt{3}/2\right) & \mapsto\sigma_{b}=\frac{1}{4}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -\sqrt{3}\\
-\sqrt{3} & 3
\end{array}\right)\nonumber \\
\psi_{C}=\left(\sqrt{3}/2,1/2\right) & \mapsto\sigma_{C}=\frac{1}{4}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & \sqrt{3}\\
\sqrt{3} & 3
\end{array}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{a}\sigma_{A}=0,\qquad\sigma_{b}\sigma_{B}=0,\qquad\sigma_{c}\sigma_{C}=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One defines other preparation procedure 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{aA}$
\end_inset

 starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A}$
\end_inset

 with the choice being made uniformly at random (toss a coin with no record
 being made of the choice).
 Similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{bB}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{cC}$
\end_inset

.
 The same procedure for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{abc}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ABC}$
\end_inset

.In the quantum formalism we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
I/2= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right)\nonumber \\
= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\sigma_{a}+\sigma_{A}\right)\nonumber \\
= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\sigma_{b}+\sigma_{B}\right)\nonumber \\
= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\sigma_{c}+\sigma_{C}\right)\nonumber \\
= & \frac{1}{3}\left(\sigma_{a}+\sigma_{b}+\sigma_{c}\right)\nonumber \\
= & \frac{1}{3}\left(\sigma_{A}+\sigma_{B}+\sigma_{C}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset


