\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:statesconfiguration"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Pictorial representation of five decomposition of the completely mixed states.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us assume that the thesis is not true.
 Hence given 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{x}$
\end_inset

 there exists a probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\left[P_{x}\right]}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 on the ontological level for a noncontextual preparation procedure quantum
 theory.
 Whetever is the context of the preparation procedure the state 
\begin_inset Formula $I/2$
\end_inset

 must not depend on the particular preparation according to the definition
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\left[P_{x}\right]}\left(\lambda\right)=\mu_{I/2}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ P_{aA},P_{bB},P_{cC},P_{abc},P_{ABC}\right\} \subseteq\left[P_{x}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:(distinguishability)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 distinguishable preparation procedures are represented by nonoverlapping
 ontological distributions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{a}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{A}\left(\lambda\right)=0,\;\mu_{b}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{B}\left(\lambda\right)=0\;\mu_{c}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{C}\left(\lambda\right)=0.\label{eq:nonoverlappingdistribution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Futhermore, even for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{aA},P_{bB},P_{cC},P_{abc},P_{ABC}$
\end_inset

 correspond the following ontological distributions via 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:(convex-combination)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mu_{aA}\left(\lambda\right)= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\mu_{a}\left(\lambda\right)+\mu_{A}\left(\lambda\right)\right)\nonumber \\
\mu_{bB}\left(\lambda\right)= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\mu_{b}\left(\lambda\right)+\mu_{B}\left(\lambda\right)\right)\nonumber \\
\mu_{cC}\left(\lambda\right)= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\mu_{c}\left(\lambda\right)+\mu_{C}\left(\lambda\right)\right)\nonumber \\
\mu_{abc}\left(\lambda\right)= & \frac{1}{3}\left(\mu_{a}\left(\lambda\right)+\mu_{b}\left(\lambda\right)+\mu_{c}\left(\lambda\right)\right)\nonumber \\
\mu_{ABC}\left(\lambda\right)= & \frac{1}{3}\left(\mu_{A}\left(\lambda\right)+\mu_{B}\left(\lambda\right)+\mu_{C}\left(\lambda\right)\right).\label{eq:convexsumdistribution}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Thus we required the equalities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{aA}=\mu_{bB}=\mu_{cC}=\mu_{abc}=\mu_{ABC}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonoverlappingdistribution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:convexsumdistribution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 holds for a fixed ontic state 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to see that the only solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{aA}=\mu_{bB}=\mu_{cC}=\mu_{abc}=\mu_{ABC}=0$
\end_inset

 which is not an ontological probability distribution.
 In fact 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{x}\mu_{X}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a,b,c$
\end_inset

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $X=A,B,C$
\end_inset

 means that one is vanishing.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{x}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a,b,c$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\left[P_{x}\right]}\left(\lambda\right)=0$
\end_inset

 in the 4th row, hence even 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X=A,B,C$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}\mu_{b}\mu_{C}=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\mu_{c}=\frac{1}{3}\mu_{c}$
\end_inset

, and it goes back to the first case.
 The other case restore this two situations.
 
\color red
Is this proof very general? Since we proof for the maximally mixed state
 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 can be a component of the maximally mixed state, I think this proof is
 ok(shed light).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remarkable, this proof states that exists an ontological model, but it does
 not depend on the particular ontological model 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 (deterministic or indeterministic or something else) .
 
\color red
We forget about the ontological and the epistemic view of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 
\color inherit
The key point is that the existance of an ontological model forces the operation
al theory to be contextual for preparation procedure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contextuality for unsharp measurements in 2D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Given a noncontextual measurement procedure ontological model for a quantum
 theory 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\color red
and the outcomes determinism assumption
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Longrightarrow\nexists$
\end_inset

 an ontological set of indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{\left[M_{x}\right],k}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{\left[M_{x}\right],k}\left(\lambda\right)=\xi_{\left\{ E_{k}\right\} _{k},k}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\Lambda}\xi_{E_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{\rho_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\,\mathrm{d}\lambda=\mathrm{Tr}\left(\rho_{k}E_{k}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 (which satisfied the epistemic outcomes).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
How to associated the msmt procedure at the ontological level? By distribution
 probability.
 In the outcomes determinism such distributions are 0 or 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Contrarly to the preparation and trasnformation noncontextuality+ontological
 model is inconsistent with qm, for msmt contextuality you must assume also
 outcome determinism.
 The Beltrametti-Bugaski model is msms noncontextual but violates outcome
 determinism and it is consistent with qm.
 Therefore you really need of both msmst noncontextuality and outcome determinis
m.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\noindent
\align block
Let the following msmt procedure 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a},M_{b},M_{c}$
\end_inset

 associate to the PVMs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Pi_{a},\Pi_{A}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Pi_{b},\Pi_{B}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Pi_{c},\Pi_{C}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in quantum operational formalism.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a,b,c$
\end_inset

 after the msmt 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{x}$
\end_inset

 the states collapse in one of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Pi_{x},\Pi_{X}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and it is projected onto the ray spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a,\dots,C$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of a PVM 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Pi_{x},\Pi_{X}\right\} $
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{x}+\Pi_{X}=I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{x}\Pi_{X}=0$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a,b,c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X=A,B,C$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that the for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{x}$
\end_inset

 the eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a,A,\dots,C$
\end_inset

.
 Let us assume the outcome determinism for PVM (sharp) at ontological level,
 hence the sets of idempotent indicator functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \chi_{I_{x}}\left(\lambda\right),\chi_{I_{X}}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a,b,c$
\end_inset

.
 By definition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi_{I_{x}}\left(\lambda\right)+\chi_{I_{X}}\left(\lambda\right)=1\qquad\chi_{I_{x}}\left(\lambda\right)\chi_{I_{X}}\left(\lambda\right)=0.\label{eq:ontological_PVM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{X}$
\end_inset

 are the ontological regions associated respectively to the projectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{x}\cup I_{X}=\Lambda$
\end_inset

 after the msmt 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{x}$
\end_inset

 the state is projected on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{x}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover from 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{b}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{c}$
\end_inset

 one can construct another msmt procedure 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 described by the POVM 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \frac{1}{3}\left(\Pi_{a}+\Pi_{b}+\Pi_{c}\right),\frac{1}{3}\left(\Pi_{A}+\Pi_{B}+\Pi_{C}\right)\right\} =\left\{ I/2,I/2\right\} $
\end_inset

 which correspond at the ontological level the set of indicator functions
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\{ \frac{1}{3}\left(\chi_{I_{a}}\left(\lambda\right)+\chi_{I_{b}}\left(\lambda\right)+\chi_{I_{c}}\left(\lambda\right)\right),\frac{1}{3}\left(\chi_{I_{A}}\left(\lambda\right)+\chi_{I_{B}}\left(\lambda\right)+\chi_{I_{C}}\left(\lambda\right)\right)\right\} .\label{eq:POVMcontextual}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Regardless the preparation procedure 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 for this POVM we have always the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr\rho I/2}=1/2$
\end_inset

 outcome.
 Then, It follows that the equivalence class of msmt procedure that contains
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 also contains the msmt 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{M}$
\end_inset

 that ignore the system and just flips a fair coin to determine the outcome.
 Let us see at the ontological level.
 Since the outcome does not depend on the system at all, regardless the
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 there is the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 for each outcome, so it is represented by the set of indicator function
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\{ \frac{1}{2}\chi_{I_{a}\cup I_{b}\cup I_{c}}\left(\lambda\right),\frac{1}{2}\chi_{I_{A}\cup I_{B}\cup I_{C}}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} =\left\{ \frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right\} .\label{eq:indicatorfunctioncontextual}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:POVMcontextual"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 must be the same of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:indicatorfunctioncontextual"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, but this is not consistent with the previuos constrains in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ontological_PVM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The eight possible assignments of values to these six quantities leave
 the set of function 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:POVMcontextual"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,0\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \frac{2}{3},\frac{1}{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

, but never 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another proof is based on the 2D version of the Gleason's theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark

\color red
Can I add something connected with the Lebesgue decomposition theorem connected
 with outcome determinism assumption?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Given an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists$
\end_inset

 a probability measure that assigns a unique probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E=I$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi\left(I\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}E_{k}=I$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}\varpi\left(E_{k}\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 In general 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varpi\left(E\right)=\mathrm{Tr}\rho E,\qquad\rho\in\mathcal{B}_{1}\left(\mathscr{H}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color red
Far from here GNS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that, at the ontological level the values of a set of indicator functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 at a particular of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 form a probability distribution over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
In a msmt noncontextual such properties works at the ontological level.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall E>0\Rightarrow\exists\vert$
\end_inset

 the ontological representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{E}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 at the operational level is associated at ontological level the unit function.
 Finally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}E_{k}=I$
\end_inset

 ontologically it turns out 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}\xi_{E_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the set of all indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{E_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 for a given value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in an ontological model satisfy the assumptions of the set of probability
 measumres in the feneralized Gleason's theorem at the operational level.
 It follows therefore that 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\:\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\rho_{\lambda}:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{E}\left(\lambda\right)=\mathrm{Tr}\left(\rho_{\lambda}E\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If in addition to M-noncontextuality, one assumes outcome determinism for
 sharp msmt 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow\forall P$
\end_inset

 projector 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists|$
\end_inset

 the representation in the ontological model by a idempotent indicator function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{P}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 and by the generalized Gleason's theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{P}\left(\lambda\right)=\mathrm{Tr}\left(\rho_{\lambda}P\right)\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\left|\psi\right\rangle \left\langle \psi\right|$
\end_inset

 and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{P}\left(\lambda\right)=\mathrm{Tr}\left(\rho_{\lambda}P\right)=1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\lambda}=\left|\psi\right\rangle \left\langle \psi\right|$
\end_inset

.
\color red
What I want to do?
\color inherit
 Let us consider 
\begin_inset Formula $P'=\left|\psi'\right\rangle \left\langle \psi'\right|$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\left|\left\langle \psi|\psi'\right\rangle \right|^{2}<1$
\end_inset

.
 At the ontological level we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{P'}\left(\lambda\right)=\mathrm{Tr}\left(\rho_{\lambda}P'\right)=\left|\left\langle \psi|\psi'\right\rangle \right|^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $0<\chi_{P'}\left(\lambda\right)<1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{P'}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 is not idempotent.
 Finally, M-noncontextual and outcome determinism yialds a contradiction
 in a 2d Hilbert space with the qm statistics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color red
This no-go theorem is related to the no-go theorem of the previous section
 in the same way that the no-go theorem [1] that is obtained from the standard
 Gleason’s theorem [7] is related to the original Kochen-Specker theorem
 [2].
 The former derive a contradiction using the full set of measurements, while
 the latter only make use of a finite set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contextuality for Transformation in 2D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
bitrary preparation is an easy iteration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
In a noncontextual trasformation procedure ontological model for a quantum
 theory 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{x}\Longrightarrow\nexists$
\end_inset

 an ontological transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\mathcal{T}}\left(\lambda',\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\left[T\right]}\left(\lambda',\lambda\right)=\Gamma_{\mathcal{T}}\left(\lambda',\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 (which satisfied the epistemic transformation) for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\lambda'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\noindent
\align block
Let a set of six transformation at the ontological level 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\vartheta}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta=0,\,\frac{\pi}{3},\,\frac{2\pi}{3},\,\pi,\,\frac{4\pi}{3},\,\frac{5\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

 it corresponds at the operational level the CP map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}_{\vartheta}\left(\rho\right)=U_{y,\vartheta}\rho U_{y,\vartheta}^{\dagger},\qquad U_{y,\vartheta}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\frac{\vartheta}{2} & -\sin\frac{\vartheta}{2}\\
\sin\frac{\vartheta}{2} & \cos\frac{\vartheta}{2}
\end{array}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the unitary operator describing a rotation by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta$
\end_inset

 about the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 axis in the Bloch sphere.
 By this transformations we can build a new one 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{x}$
\end_inset

 that takes all points in the Bloch sphere and projects them onto the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 axis.
 There are many ways to implement 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{x}$
\end_inset

, specifically,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{T}_{x}= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\mathcal{T}_{0}+\mathcal{T}_{\pi}\right)\\
= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\mathcal{T}_{\frac{\pi}{3}}+\mathcal{T}_{\frac{4\pi}{3}}\right)\\
= & \frac{1}{2}\left(\mathcal{T}_{\frac{2\pi}{3}}+\mathcal{T}_{\frac{5\pi}{3}}\right)\\
= & \frac{1}{3}\left(\mathcal{T}_{0}+\mathcal{T}_{\frac{2\pi}{3}}+\mathcal{T}_{\frac{4\pi}{3}}\right)\\
= & \frac{1}{3}\left(\mathcal{T}_{\frac{\pi}{3}}+\mathcal{T}_{\pi}+\mathcal{T}_{\frac{5\pi}{3}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This transformation is an endomorfism onto the states in fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:statesconfiguration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The T-noncontextuality assumes that for each of these seven transformations
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\vartheta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is associated on the space of ontic states a unique transition matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\vartheta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{x}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Analogously to the lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:convexsumdistribution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 a convex sum of transformation procedures is represented in an ontological
 model by a convex sum of the associated transition matrices, than
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T_{x}= & \frac{1}{2}\left(T_{0}+T_{\pi}\right)\\
= & \frac{1}{2}\left(T_{\frac{\pi}{3}}+T_{\frac{4\pi}{3}}\right)\\
= & \frac{1}{2}\left(T_{\frac{2\pi}{3}}+T_{\frac{5\pi}{3}}\right)\\
= & \frac{1}{3}\left(T_{0}+T_{\frac{2\pi}{3}}+T_{\frac{4\pi}{3}}\right)\\
= & \frac{1}{3}\left(T_{\frac{\pi}{3}}+T_{\pi}+T_{\frac{5\pi}{3}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\vartheta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\vartheta+\pi}$
\end_inset

 map any 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 lying in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z-x$
\end_inset

 plane of the Bloch sphere to a pair of orthogonal density operators.
 Orthogonality at operational level correspond to nonoverlapping ontological
 distribution (wheter we assume ontic or epistemic view, as we show later).
 It follows from lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:(distinguishability)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that the trnasition matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\vartheta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\vartheta+\pi}$
\end_inset

 must take any distrubition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{x}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 to disjoint distributions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{\rho_{\vartheta}}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{\rho_{\vartheta+\pi}}\left(\lambda\right)=\int_{\Lambda}T_{\vartheta}\left(\lambda,\lambda'\right)\mu_{x}\left(\lambda'\right)d\lambda'\int_{\Lambda}T_{\vartheta+\pi}\left(\lambda,\lambda'\right)\mu_{x}\left(\lambda'\right)d\lambda'=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now consider how our seven transition matrices affect the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 represented at the operational level by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 We restor exactly the contradiction for P-noncontextuality.
 This contradiction is due to the fact that we assume for T-noncontextual
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\left[\mathcal{T}\right]}\left(\lambda',\lambda\right)=\Gamma_{T}\left(\lambda',\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

, but we have demostrated that it is not possible be consistent with qm.
 
\color red
Expoit as exercise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
P-noncontextuality assumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traditionally noncontextuality is restricted only to the definitino of M-noncont
extuality for sharp msmt.
 Is it natural to extent the assumption even for P- and T-noncontextualityand
 for M-noncontextuality for unsharp msmt? First of all, let us see why contextua
lity is a mystery in need of explanation.
 One can assume that nonlocality is a good assumption, unless the classical
 concepts.
 Therefore let us assume that the universe is fundamentally nonseparable
 or that such causal influences can propagate faster than the speed of light.
 It seems almost cospirational that it is not possible superluminal communicatio
n.
 Analogously, let us assume that the qunatum statistics depend on the detail
 (context) of the experiment.
 It is reasonable.
 But, then, it is very surprising that when one considers any valid probabiliry
 distribution over the ontic states ( that is, any distribution that characteriz
es what someone who knows only the preparation procedure knows about the
 ontic state) the weighted average over the statistics of outcomes does
 not depend on the detail of the experimental procedures.
 Both the examples apprear cospirational.
 Removing appear of cospirational from contextuality as the same worth of
 the reconciling between relativity and Bell's theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us focus on the attention only for P-noncontextuality.
 To answer if it is natural or not we need to define the epistemic view
 and the ontic view of pure states.
 For mixed states the ontological interpretation is the same, they represent
 the partial knowledfe of the whole system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ontic view) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 the space of pure states, an ontological model adopts an ontic view of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 if all distinct elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 are represented by disjoint distributions in the ontological model, that
 it 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho\neq\rho'\Rightarrow\mu_{\rho}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{\rho'}\left(\lambda\right)=0\quad\forall\rho,\rho'\in\mathcal{S}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
disjoint distributions corresponds to different elements of reality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(epistemic view) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 the space of pure states, an ontological model adopts an epistemic view
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 if only orthogonal operational elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 are represented by disjoint distributions in the ontological model, that
 it 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho\perp\rho'\Rightarrow\mu_{\rho}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{\rho'}\left(\lambda\right)=0\quad\forall\rho,\rho'\in\mathcal{S}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Of course 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\perp\rho'\Rightarrow\rho\neq\rho'$
\end_inset

, therefore orthogonality at the operational level is a sufficient condition
 for disjointness in the ontological level wheter one adopts an ontic or
 an epistem view.
 In other words, the request of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\neq\rho'$
\end_inset

 in the ontic view implies that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 correspond an element of reality different from other elements of reality.
 Instead, from the epistemic point of view 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 represent only partial knowledge of that element of reality 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 which can have other information in 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho'\neq\rho$
\end_inset

, and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\perp\rho'$
\end_inset

 we have different elements of reality even for the epistemic view.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
An ontic view of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 rules out the possibility of preparation noncontextuality trivially.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
An implicit commitment to such a view can lead to the impression that the
 assumption of prepration noncontextuality is unnatural.
 Consider the preparation procedure above 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{x}$
\end_inset

 represented in quantum formalism via 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 giving 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a,A,b,B$
\end_inset

.
 An ontic view of pure quantum states implies that nt onlu are the orthogonal
 stetes associated with disjoint distrubitions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mu_{a}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{A}\left(\lambda\right) & =0\\
\mu_{b}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{B}\left(\lambda\right) & =0
\end{align}

\end_inset

but also nonorthogonal states area associated with disjoint distributions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mu_{a}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{b}\left(\lambda\right) & =0\\
\mu_{a}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{B}\left(\lambda\right) & =0\\
\mu_{A}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{b}\left(\lambda\right) & =0\\
\mu_{A}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{B}\left(\lambda\right) & =0
\end{align}

\end_inset

It is then clear that the preparation procedure at the operational level
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{aA}\longleftrightarrow1/2\left(\sigma_{a}+\sigma_{A}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{bB}\longleftrightarrow1/2\left(\sigma_{b}+\sigma_{B}\right)$
\end_inset

 are represented by distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{aA}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{bB}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{aA}\mu_{bB}=0$
\end_inset

.
 It is not possible because both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{aA}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{bB}$
\end_inset

 are represented by the same density operator at the operational level,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $I/2$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{aA}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{bB}$
\end_inset

 must be represented by the same ontological distribution in the P-noncontextual
 ontological model.
 Thus the ontic view of quantum pure states trivially precludes the possibility
 of P-noncontextuality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Implicit commitment comes form the natural language which brings to the
 idea that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 represent some real quantity rather than the agent's knowledge.
 For instance, describing the photon polarization, the several convex decomposit
ions of the completely mixed states 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto I$
\end_inset

 sometimes is thought as an equal mixture of states of horizontal and vertical
 polarization, or as an equal mixture of statesof left and right circular
 polarization.
 This two preparations are statistically indistinguishable.
 This four states of polarization can be thought as mutually exclusive states
 of affair and are therefore ontic states.
 But from the epistemic point of view we can refer to the same element of
 reality.
 Even if this two preparations are statistically indistinguishable, there
 exists some msmt that could tell these two cases apart? In virtue of the
 fact that the answer is negative, since it is connected only to a common
 language and not to a rigorous model, the naturalness of P-noncontextuality
 is a priori very plausible in the perspective of the epistemic view.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The impossibility of a preparation noncontextual ontological model appears
 all the more shockhing to the devoted realist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Outcome determinism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the proof of M-contextuality we assume outcome determinism for PVM (sharp
 msmt), which are idempotent indicator function in the ontological model,
 and outcome indeterminism for POVM (unsharp msmt), which are nonidempotent
 indicator functions in the ontological model.
 The notion of M-noncontextual does not depends on this assumptions.
 This assumption seem very natural, but there exist other assumption a priori
 very plausible, as well: (1) PVM and POVM are outcome determinism; (2)
 or outcome indeterminism (3)Toner, Bacon Ben-Or (4) Bacciagaluppi
\series bold
[to cite]
\series default
.
 Let us start from the first case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume outcome determinism also for unsharp msmt.
 In M-noncontextuality consider a msmt procedure 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{x}$
\end_inset

 associated with POVM 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ I/2,I/2\right\} $
\end_inset

 must be represented in an ontological model by the sep of indicator functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1/2,1/2\right\} $
\end_inset

 which are not idempotent, and thus in a M-noncontextual ontological model
 outcome determinism of unsharp msmt is not allowed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second alternative consitutes the weakest assumption and consequentlu
 the most general framework for an ontological model.
 It should be inappropriate to call no-go theorem our theorem for M-contextualit
y for qm,if we do not justify the assumption of outcome determinism.
 The noncontextuality should be inconsistent with epistemic statistics of
 qm because of outcome determinism and not because M-contextuality.
 Therefore the outcome determinism assumption should be a natural consequence
 of the M-noncontextuality assumption.
 If it is not the case, the proof, and any other proof as Bell's theorem,
 Kochen-Specker serve to rule out the possibility of M-noncontextuality.
 It turns out, however that the assumption of outcome determinism for sharp
 msmt can be justified by an assumption of P-noncontextuality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
P-noncontextuality assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 outcome determinism for sharp msmt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We demostrate in two steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\cup_{k}\Omega_{k}\Rightarrow\left\{ \xi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}=\left\{ \chi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 the set of indicator function is idempotent(outcome determinism)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
P-noncontextuality 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mu_{\left[P\right]}\left(\lambda\right)=\mu_{P}\left(\lambda\right)\right)\Rightarrow\Lambda=\cup_{k}\Omega_{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let a rank-1 PVM 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Pi_{k}\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{k}=\rho_{k}$
\end_inset

 which constitutes an orthogonal set of rank-1 density operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \rho_{k}\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

.
 We use different notation because they are represented differently in the
 ontological model.
 The operational set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Pi_{k}\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 is represented by a set of indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 and the operational set of density operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \rho_{k}\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 is represented by a set of probability densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mu_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \rho_{k}\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal for the lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:(distinguishability)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\Omega_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{\Omega_{k'}}\left(\lambda\right)=\delta_{k,k'}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{k}\cap\Omega_{k'}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq k'$
\end_inset

.
 The P-noncontextual ontological model must be compatible a priori with
 the epistemic statistics given by the Bohr's rule 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Tr}\left(\rho_{k}\Pi_{k'}\right)=\delta_{k,k'},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

therefore in the ontological model, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{\Lambda}\xi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{\Omega_{k'}}\left(\lambda\right)d\lambda= & \int_{\cup_{k}\Omega_{k}}\xi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{\Omega_{k'}}\left(\lambda\right)d\lambda\\
= & \int_{\Omega_{k'}}\xi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\mu_{\Omega_{k'}}\left(\lambda\right)d\lambda=\delta_{k,k'}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The second equality is due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{k}=\left\{ \lambda|\:\mu_{\Omega_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)>0\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the last is due to the compatibility with the operational level.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \lambda\in\Omega_{k}\\
0 & \lambda\not\in\Omega_{k}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{k}\left(\lambda\right)\xi_{k'}\left(\lambda\right)=\delta_{k,k'}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda=\cup_{k}\Omega_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the second point, let us notice that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda=\left\{ \lambda|\:\mu_{\rho}\left(\lambda\right)>0\:\text{for some }\rho\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

However, ince every density operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 appears in some convex decomposition od the completely mixed state 
\begin_inset Formula $I/d$
\end_inset

, and since P-noncontextuality implies that there is a unique distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{I/d}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 associated with this state, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is simply the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 assigned non-zero probability by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{I/d}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda=\left\{ \lambda|\:\mu_{I/d}\left(\lambda\right)>0\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

But given that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{k}$
\end_inset

 form a convex decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $I/d$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{k}\frac{1}{d}\mu_{k}\left(\lambda\right)=\mu_{I/d}\left(\lambda\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which implies the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\cup_{k}\Omega_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 This esthablishes outcome determinism for PVMs all of whose elements are
 rank 1.
 Since an arbitrary PVM can always be obtained by coarse-grainig of rank-1
 PVM, and since coarse-graning takes idempotent functions to idempotetn
 functions, any PVM is represented by a set of idempotent indicator functions.
 This establishes that the assumption of outcome determinism for sharp msmt
 follows from the assumption of preparation noncontextuality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
M-noncontextuality 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

outcome determinism? No.
 If this were possible then we do not need to assume the extra hypothesis
 of outcome determinism to achieve the no-go theorem.
 Without this assumption M-noncontextuality on its own is consisten the
 qm (below).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
What's happen for oblique PVM which sum to the identity? Try to play with
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{+}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
\alpha & 0
\end{array}\right),\qquad P_{-}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
\alpha & 1
\end{array}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
M-noncontextuality without outcome determinism assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 compatible with qm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Assumption: objectively indeterministic ontological model of quantum theory
 and ontic view.
 The ontic space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is simply the set of the Hilbert rays which are the element of the projective
 Hilbert space.
 Thus for every rank-1 projector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle \left\langle \psi\right|$
\end_inset

 at the operational level corresponds an ontic state called 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 There are not hidden variable in this ontological model.
 A preparation procedure in the ontological model associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi'\right\rangle \left\langle \psi'\right|$
\end_inset

 is represented as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{\psi'}\left(\psi\right)=\delta\left(\psi-\psi'\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A preparation procedure involving a convex combination of rank-1 density
 operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ p\left(\psi'\right),\left|\psi'\right\rangle \left\langle \psi'\right|\right\} _{\psi'}$
\end_inset

 is represented by the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu\left(\psi\right)=\int_{\Lambda}p\left(\psi'\right)\delta\left(\psi-\psi'\right)\,\mathrm{d}\psi',
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\psi'$
\end_inset

 is the Lebesgue measure on the projective Hilbert space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
A msmt of POVM 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ Q_{k}\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 is associated with a set of indicator functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{Q_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi_{Q_{k}}\left(\psi\right)=\mathrm{Tr}\left(Q_{k}\left|\psi\right\rangle \left\langle \psi\right|\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These functions are clearly positive by the positivityof 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 and sum to unit by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}Q_{k}=I$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{Q_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 depend only on the POVM that is associated with the msmt and not on how
 it was implemented.
 One can see that this model reproduce quantum theory noting that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\Lambda}\mu_{\psi'}\left(\psi\right)\xi_{Q_{k}}\left(\psi\right)\,\mathrm{d}\psi=\mathrm{Tr}\left(Q_{k}\left|\psi'\right\rangle \left\langle \psi'\right|\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\color red
but the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{Q_{k}}\left(\lambda\right)\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 associated with any PVM 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Pi_{k}\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset

 is not idempotent.
 This is clear since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}\left(\Pi_{k}\left|\psi\right\rangle \left\langle \psi\right|\right)$
\end_inset

 s only 0 or 1 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 lies in an eigenspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The predictions for mixed preparation are also reproduced
\series bold
